Ethernet is the most common wired network technology used to connect devices within a LAN. Ethernet LANs are typically found in homes, offices, and schools, allowing devices to share resources and communicate with each other. An Ethernet LAN consists of both physical and logical components. Physical components include the network cables (both twisted-pair and fiber-optic), network interface cards (NICs), switches, and routers. In the figure, both twisted-pair (blue) and fiber-optic (orange) cables are shown.

A MAC (Media Access Control) address is a unique number assigned to a device’s network card so it can be identified on a network.
