In a small network, you can manually configure each device with proper IP addressing. You would assign a unique IP address to each host within the same network. This is known as static IP addressing.
On a Windows computer, as shown in the figure on the left, you can assign the following IPv4 address configuration information to a host:
IP address - identifies this device on the network
Subnet mask - is used to identify the network on which this device is connected
Default gateway - identifies the router that this device uses to access the internet or another network
Optional values - such as the preferred Domain Name System (DNS) server address and the alternate DNS server address

Rather than manually configure every device, you can take advantage of implementing a Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) server. A DHCP server automatically assigns IP addresses, which simplifies the addressing process. Automatically configuring some of the IP addressing parameters also reduces the possibility of assigning duplicate or invalid IP addresses.

A DHCP server can automatically assign the following IPv4 address configuration information to a host:
IPv4 address
Subnet mask
Default gateway
Optional values, such as a DNS server address

Unicast = one sender → one receiver
Broadcast = One sender → Everyone on the network
Multicast = One sender → A group of devices
The packet goes only to devices that joined a specific group, not everyone.

Unlike IPv4 devices that usually have only a single address, IPv6 devices typically have two unicast addresses:

Global Unicast Address (GUA) - This is similar to a public IPv4 address. These are globally unique, internet-routable addresses. GUAs can be configured statically or assigned dynamically.
Link-Local Address (LLA) - This is required for every IPv6-enabled device. LLAs are used to communicate with other devices on the same local link. LLAs are confined to a single link. Their uniqueness must only be confirmed on that link because they are not routable beyond the link. In other words, routers will not forward packets with a link-local source or destination address.

A device can send a packet to the following:
1- Itself - A device can ping itself by sending a packet to a special IPv4 address of 127.0.0.1 or an IPv6 address ::1, which is referred to as the loopback interface. Pinging the loopback interface tests that networking is functioning on the device.
2- Local device - This is a destination device that is on the same local network as the sending device. The source and destination devices share the same network address. For example, all the devices in your home are probably on the same network.
3- Remote device - This is a destination device on a remote network. The source and destination devices do not share the same network address. For example, when you visit a website, you are sending packets to a remote network.

Whether a packet is destined for a local host or a remote host is determined by the source device. The source device determines whether the destination IP address is on the same network that the source device itself is on. The method of determination varies by IP version:
In IPv4 - The source device uses its own subnet mask along with its own IPv4 address and the destination IPv4 address to make this determination.
In IPv6 - The local router advertises the local network address (prefix) to all devices on the network.

The default gateway is the network device, such as a router, that can route traffic to other networks. If you use the analogy that a network is like a room, then the default gateway is like a doorway. In the figure, R1 is the default gateway. If you want to get to another room or network you need to find the doorway.

On a network, a default gateway is usually a router with these features:

It has a local IP address in the same address range as other hosts on the local network.
It can accept data into the local network and forward data out of the local network.
It routes traffic to other networks.
A default gateway is required to send traffic outside of the local network. Traffic cannot be forwarded outside the local network if there is no default gateway, the default gateway address is not configured, or the default gateway is down.

On a Windows host, the route print or netstat -r command can be used to display the host routing table. Both commands generate the same output. The output may seem overwhelming at first, but is fairly simple to understand.

Troubleshooting Default Gateway Issues
There are a number of issues that can arise if the incorrect default gateway address or subnet mask is configured on a device:
1- No internet access: If a device is assigned the wrong default gateway address, it will be unable to reach IP addresses that are on remote networks. Verify the router interface address and the default gateway address configured on the devices is the same. Often, the default gateway address is distributed through DHCP. Ensure that the DHCP server is configured with the correct gateway address.
2- Some devices can communicate to remote networks, others on the same network cannot: If the subnet mask configured on a device does not match the subnet mask (or prefix length) configured on its default gateway, the device may not be able to correctly identify which destination addresses are on its local IP subnet and which ones are located on remote networks. Verify that all devices on the same local IP network are configured with same subnet mask as the default gateway interface address.

Routers are networking devices that connect multiple networks and direct traffic between them based on the destination IP address. This is crucial for connecting geographically dispersed branches to a central office, as it enables efficient data transfer and communication over long distances.

