DNS, or the Domain Name System, is the "phone book" of the internet. On the internet, fully-qualified domain names (FQDNs), such as http://www.cisco.com, are much easier for people to remember than 198.133.219.25, which is the actual numeric IP address for one of Cisco’s servers. You can verify that yourself by searching for “whois 198.133.219.25”.
If Cisco decides to change the numeric IP address of www.cisco.com, it is transparent to the user because the domain name remains the same. The new address is simply linked to the existing domain name and connectivity is maintained.

Initial Query: The first time a website address is requested, your device asks a DNS server for its IP address. It then stores (or "caches") that address locally.
Fast Recall: If you visit the same website again, your device checks its local cache first. If the IP address is already saved, it skips asking the DNS server and loads the website faster.
Expiration (Time-to-Live or TTL): DNS cache isn’t permanent. It has a "time-to-live" (TTL) limit. After the TTL expires, your device deletes the cached address and has to ask the DNS server again.

There are alternative methods available that can provide an automatic IP address to a device when it becomes active on a network. These alternatives differ between IPv4 and IPv6.

Windows IPv4 APIPA

In IPv4, the Windows operating system provides a method to automatically generate an IPv4 address using APIPA (Automatic Private IP Addressing). APIPA assigns an IP address in the range 169.254.0.1 to 169.254.255.254 when no static IP address is assigned and no DHCP server responds. This allows basic local network communication with other devices that are assigned APIPA addresses but does not provide internet connectivity.

IPv6 must have a link-local address. If an LLA is not configured manually on an interface, the device will automatically create its own without communicating with a DHCP server. Recall that IPv6 link-local addresses are in the fe80::/10 range.

In IPv6, there is another method of automatic address assignment that hosts can use to generate their own routable IPv6 addressing. Using the Stateless Address Autoconfiguration (SLAAC) available in IPv6 networks, hosts can configure their own addresses. Using this method, hosts receive the network prefix advertised by routers on their network segment and append their own unique identifier (usually the MAC address of the network interface).

Autoconfiguration Issues

Issues that arise from autoconfiguration include:
Duplicate address conflicts: Autoconfiguration relies on the device being able to identify addresses that are already in use on the network. If an error occurs, there may be duplicate addresses assigned.
APIPA limitation: Windows devices automatically configured with an APIPA address are usually set to get their IP address through DHCP. When a DHCP server cannot be reached, the APIPA address is assigned. This prevents internet connectivity.
IPv6 autogenerated address errors: IPv6 SLAAC relies on network broadcasts to identify the network prefix. A device may incorrectly derive its IPv6 address, leading to loss of connectivity.

Many home networks and small businesses use a wireless router and modem. In this case, the wireless router is both a DHCP client and a server. The wireless router acts as a client to receive its IPv4 configuration from the ISP and then acts as a DHCP server for internal hosts on the local network. The router receives the public IPv4 address from the ISP, and in its role as a DHCP server, it distributes private addresses to internal hosts.

In addition to PC-based servers and wireless routers, other types of networking devices such as dedicated routers can provide DHCP services to clients, although this is not as common.

Devices (clients) ask for an IP address.
The DHCP server gives them one from its available range (scope).
The IP is leased temporarily.
