SLAAC (Stateless Address Autoconfiguration) is a feature in IPv6 that allows devices to automatically generate their own globally routable IP addresses based on the network prefix advertised by routers. This approach is well-suited for IoT and medical devices that need unique, routable addresses without centralized IP management.

Firewalls are the gatekeepers that protect a network from unauthorized access and malicious threats. 
A firewall protects computers and networks by preventing undesirable traffic from entering internal networks. For instance, the top topology in the figure illustrates how the firewall enables traffic from an internal network host to exit the network and return to the inside network. 

Host-based firewalls are software programs that provide firewall services on a computer to allow or deny traffic to the computer. The host-based firewall applies a set of rules to data transmissions through inspection and filtering of data packets.

Windows Defender Firewall is an example of a host-based firewall that helps prevent cybercriminals and malware from gaining access to your computer. It is installed by default when the Windows OS is installed.

ipconfig (Windows)
The ipconfig command is used to display and manage the network settings of a Windows machine. It can quickly provide details about the IP address, subnet mask, and default gateway for each network adapter on the system.

ifconfig (Linux/Unix)
Running ifconfig without any additional options provides a summary of the current network configuration. This output includes the IP address (192.168.1.105), subnet mask (255.255.255.0), and broadcast address (192.168.1.255) for the eth0 interface, as well as the hardware (MAC) address (00:0c:29:58:9b:0e) and the IPv6 LLA.

Use ipconfig /release and ipconfig /renew on Windows or sudo dhclient on Linux to request a new IP.

Use Cases for IT Support Technicians

The ping and ping6 commands are essential for:
Verifying basic network connectivity.
Measuring network latency.
Checking for packet loss.
Troubleshooting DNS resolution issues.
Confirming that a server or website is online.

The traceroute command is used to track the path that packets take to reach a destination across an IP network. It provides a detailed map of the route, including the number of hops, round-trip times, and the IP addresses of intermediate routers. 
The tracert command in Windows provides similar functionality to traceroute.

Use Cases for traceroute6
Technicians might use traceroute6 to:
Diagnose slow IPv6 connections.
Identify failing routers or broken links in IPv6 networks.
Verify the reachability of IPv6-enabled services.
Troubleshoot connectivity issues in dual-stack (IPv4 and IPv6) environments.

The nslookup command allows you to verify DNS resolution.

Use Cases for IT Support Technicians

The nslookup command is essential for:

Verifying DNS resolution for a specific domain.
Troubleshooting DNS issues when a website is unreachable.
Confirming that DNS changes have propagated correctly.
Checking for misconfigured DNS servers.
Testing both IPv4 and IPv6 connectivity.

The iproute2 suite is a powerful collection of networking utilities used to manage and configure Linux network interfaces, routing tables, and traffic control. It replaces older tools like ifconfig, route, and netstat, providing more advanced features and flexibility. It is the default networking toolset on most modern Linux distributions, including Ubuntu, CentOS, Debian, and Fedora.

An attack vector is a path by which a threat actor can gain access to a server, host, or network. Attack vectors originate from inside or outside the corporate network.

A DoS attack occurs when a network device or application is incapacitated and no longer capable of supporting requests from legitimate users.

An internal user, such as an employee, can accidentally or intentionally:

Steal and copy confidential data to removable media, email, messaging software, and other media.
Compromise internal servers or network infrastructure devices.
Disconnect a critical network connection and cause a network outage.
Connect an infected USB drive into a corporate computer system.
Internal threats have the potential to cause greater damage than external threats because internal users have direct access to the building and its infrastructure devices. Employees may also have knowledge of the corporate network, its resources, and its confidential data.

Network security professionals must implement tools and apply techniques for mitigating both external and internal threats.

Malware refers to software specifically engineered to cause harm, disrupt operations, or gain unauthorized access to computer systems. 

The first and most common type of computer malware is a virus. Viruses require human action to propagate and infect other computers. For example, a virus can infect a computer when a victim opens an email attachment, opens a file on a USB drive, or downloads a file.
The virus hides by attaching itself to computer code, software, or documents on the computer. When opened, the virus executes and infects the computer.

Viruses can:
Alter, corrupt, delete files, or erase entire drives.
Cause computer booting issues, and corrupt applications.
Capture and send sensitive information to threat actors.
Access and use email accounts to spread.
Lay dormant until summoned by the threat actor.
